The paper deals with the computational complexity of MapReduce, which is a distributed computing paradigm commonly used in data-intensive applications. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing). The paper also uses complexity-theoretic techniques to analyze the MapReduce model, which suggests that it could belong to cs.CC (Computational Complexity) or cs.IT (Information Theory). Additionally, the paper discusses the regular languages and sublogarithmic space, which are topics related to cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). Finally, the paper lays the foundation for further analysis relating MapReduce to established complexity classes, which could also place it in cs.LG (Machine Learning).
